            <section class="prose">
              <h2>Torque formula</h2>
              <p>
                In vector form, torque is defined as the cross product of the
                position vector <em>r</em> (from the axis to the point of
                application of the force) and the force vector <em>F</em>:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>\(\vec{\tau} = \vec{r} \times \vec{F}\)</p>
              </div>
              <p>
                For many practical problems (like a wrench on a bolt), we only
                need the magnitude:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>\(|\tau| = r \cdot F \cdot \sin(\theta)\)</p>
                <ul>
                  <li>
                    \(r\): distance from axis to where the force is applied
                    (lever arm)
                  </li>
                  <li>\(F\): magnitude of the force</li>
                  <li>\(\theta\): angle between \(\vec{r}\) and \(\vec{F}\)</li>
                </ul>
              </div>
              <p>
                If the force is applied perpendicular to the lever arm (\(\theta
                = 90^\circ\)), then \(\sin(\theta) = 1\) and the formula
                simplifies to:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>\(\tau = r \cdot F\)</p>
              </div>

              <h3>Solving for force or distance</h3>
              <p>Rearranging the basic formula (for \(\theta = 90^\circ\)):</p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Given torque and distance, find force:
                  <div class="formula-box">
                    <p>\(F = \dfrac{\tau}{r}\)</p>
                  </div>
                </li>
                <li>
                  Given torque and force, find distance:
                  <div class="formula-box">
                    <p>\(r = \dfrac{\tau}{F}\)</p>
                  </div>
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>Units of torque</h2>
              <p>The SI unit of torque is the newton‑metre (N·m):</p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  1 N·m = 1 newton of force applied at 1 metre from the axis,
                  perpendicular to the lever arm.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>Common engineering units:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>1 N·m ≈ 0.73756 ft·lb</li>
                <li>1 ft·lb ≈ 1.35582 N·m</li>
                <li>1 N·m = 100 N·cm = 1000 N·mm</li>
                <li>1 kgf·m ≈ 9.80665 N·m</li>
              </ul>

              <h2>Worked example</h2>
              <p>
                <strong>Example:</strong> You apply a 15 N force at the end of a
                0.25 m wrench, perpendicular to the wrench. What torque do you
                produce?
              </p>
              <p>Given:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>\(F = 15\ \text{N}\)</li>
                <li>\(r = 0.25\ \text{m}\)</li>
                <li>\(\theta = 90^\circ \Rightarrow \sin(\theta) = 1\)</li>
              </ul>
              <p>Compute:</p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>\(\tau = r \cdot F = 0.25 \times 15 = 3.75\ \text{N·m}\)</p>
              </div>
              <p>In ft·lb:</p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>
                  \(3.75\ \text{N·m} \times 0.73756 \approx 2.77\ \text{ft·lb}\)
                </p>
              </div>

              <h2>Torque vs. work and power</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Torque</strong> causes rotation; it is a vector
                  quantity.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Work</strong> is energy transferred; for rotation with
                  constant torque:
                  <div class="formula-box">
                    <p>\(W = \tau \cdot \theta\)</p>
                    <p>where \(\theta\) is in radians.</p>
                  </div>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Power</strong> in rotational motion:
                  <div class="formula-box">
                    <p>\(P = \tau \cdot \omega\)</p>
                    <p>where \(\omega\) is angular velocity in rad/s.</p>
                  </div>
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>Frequently asked questions</h2>

              <h3>What is torque in simple terms?</h3>
              <p>
                Torque is the “twisting force” that makes things rotate. Pushing
                a door near the handle is easier than near the hinges because
                the same force at a larger distance produces more torque.
              </p>

              <h3>Why does the angle matter?</h3>
              <p>
                Only the component of the force perpendicular to the lever arm
                produces torque. If the force is at an angle \(\theta\), the
                effective force is \(F_\perp = F \sin(\theta)\), so the torque
                is \(r \cdot F \cdot \sin(\theta)\).
              </p>

              <h3>Can torque be negative?</h3>
              <p>
                Yes. The sign indicates the direction of rotation relative to
                your chosen convention (e.g., counterclockwise positive,
                clockwise negative). The calculator reports magnitude; sign must
                be assigned based on your coordinate system.
              </p>
